segments.text: When Premiere Pro crashed three times in a row during my last editing session, I decided it was finally time for a change.
There had to be a better way.

Not only do I want to get away from this incredibly unstable and buggy software, but more importantly, I don't want to pay $70 per month for a bunch of crappy software as soon as my student discount ends.
So I started to look for alternatives.
Of course, there's plenty of different video editing tools out there, but I was always intrigued by the idea of programmatically created videos.
Like any other programmer, I'm obsessed with the idea of automating things, even if that means that it will take much longer than doing the work manually.
So I decided to create this video that you're watching right now completely with code.
But how does it work?
To find out, I went onto GitHub and searched for libraries for creating videos with code.
The most popular one is Manim.
It is a library created by the popular YouTuber 3Blue1Brown, who created it to animate his own YouTube videos.
It is therefore made for creating mathematical animations.
Manim looks awesome, and even though I'm not creating mathematical videos, I would have tried it out immediately if it wasn't for the fact that it is written in Python.
And let's just say I have a completely irrational and unsubstantiated hate against Python.
And if I had the power to erase Python from the history of humanity, I wouldn't hesitate for a second.
So in the interest of my mental health, I will not use Menem, but I'm sure it's great if you're willing to sacrifice your sanity.
The second tool I found is Remotion.
It is based on React and uses a headless browser to render the video, which means that you can use a lot of existing CSS features and libraries out of the box.
While it is possible to make at least a YouTube intro with Remotion, as shown in the Fireship video that I stole this video title from, the primary use case is creating data-driven videos.
Think for example data visualization or animated statistics.
But after doing some more research, I found another tool that looks like a much better option for my use case.
MotionCanvas is a TypeScript library for creating animated videos.
It was created by a GameTab YouTuber called Artificial.
who initially voted to create his own YouTube videos.
The main difference between Remotion and Motion Canvas is how the animation timeline is controlled.
With Remotion, everything that is happening is based on the current frame number that you can access via the useCurrentFrame function.
If, for example, you wanted to move an element to the right, you would just increase the X coordinate with the current frame number.
This works really well as long as you know exactly what is happening at any given point in the video, but as soon as you start to move stuff around, it can get really messy.
Unfortunately, my video creation process is already quite messy.
I add, we move and change stuff all the time while editing, so this might not be the best fit for me.
MotionCanvas has a very different approach.
Instead of calculating everything based on the frame number, you can just write what you want to happen in sequential order.
For example, we can just move an object to a certain position, wait for a second, and then move it back afterwards.
It is much more obvious what is happening, especially when we compare it to a Remotion component that would do the same animation.
So I decided to pass on Remotion.
Every animation that you've seen so far and every animation that you will see later in this video is written with Motion Canvas.
So how does it work?
There are five basic concepts that Motion Canvas uses.
As soon as you understand those concepts, you can do pretty much anything with Motion Canvas.
The first of them is Scenes.
After you create a new Motion Canvas project with an npm command, you will have a new project with one scene.
To see what this scene currently looks like, you can start the built-in editor interface, which acts more like a preview with limited editing capabilities, but more on that later.
Similar to a DOM tree, you can now add nodes to this scene and you can also nest them into each other.
Just like in React, you can use JSX to make those node trees a little bit more readable.
But don't worry, you do not need any React knowledge to use Motion Canvas.
Text is just a small abstraction layer that allows you to write notes in an XML-like syntax directly in your JavaScript code.
If you don't like that, you can just create instances of notes, nest them into each other, and add them to the scene.
Talking about notes, there are a ton of them already available.
Texts, circles, rectangles, images, videos, and even a ready-to-use code component that you have seen quite a few times at this point.
And if those are not enough, you can easily create your own notes with custom looks and functionality.
You might or might not have noticed that this node is actually centered in our scene.
That is actually the default in MotionCanvas, but let's take a closer look at how positioning works in MotionCanvas.
The origin of a scene is in the center, which might be a little confusing at first, but it's also very convenient if you just want to add a single element to the scene.
Other than that, the position of an element is always relative to its parent.
And it uses a coordinate system where increasing the X value will move it to the right and increasing the Y value will move it down.
So it's similar to CSS and HTML.
But don't worry, you don't have to position every element manually.
Even though MotionCanvas does not support CSS directly, it has a layout feature that implements a lot of Flexbox features, which makes it easy to position multiple elements in
a scene.
To create a new layout route, you can just set the Layout property on most of the basic nodes provided by Motion Canvas.
Those nodes extend the layout route in the background.
Similar to Flexbox, you can modify the vertical alignment, the horizontal alignment, gaps between the elements, and the direction of the element flow.
Making it a powerful tool that saved me a lot of effort and time while creating this video.
Now that we have our nodes in our scene and we know how to position them, how do we actually make them move?
Let's take a look at how animations work.
You might have noticed this yield keyword in some of the earlier code snippets.
MotionCanvas uses a concept called generators under the hood.
And I honestly had no idea that this exists in JavaScript.
While I might be guilty of having copied and pasted some code in other languages that uses generators, I never really cared enough to understand the concept.
But it's actually really cool and makes a lot of sense for something like video generation.
So let's do a quick crash course, just in case you have the same skill issues as me.
Generators are special functions with a star behind the function keyword.
Inside of those generator functions, you can use the yield keyword which acts similar to a return in the way that it stops the function from further executing and returns a value.
But unlike regular functions, you can continue the execution by calling the next function on the generator.

For that reason, they are also known as lazy iterators because once you create a generator object, you can call the next function and it will continue the execution of the generator until the next yield and return the yield value.
And you can also add code between the yield statements, which is only executed when the next function is called.
Now motion canvas uses yield for every frame rendered.
So it will apply the changes between two frames in between those yield statements.
That might sound a little tedious, but motion canvas handles all of that under
the hood and the functions that you will use to animate objects are actually really straightforward.
To move a circle, we can just write dot position dot x and call it with the position that we want to move it to and the duration for the animation in seconds.
So this will move the circle to a position of 300 over the span of one second.
As a third argument, we can pass an easing function to make the animations smooth as butter.
The properties that you are able to animate will depend on the node that you're using.
And most of the properties are already ready to be animated like position, scale, rotation, or even rounded corners.
But if you want to add your own animated attributes, you can do that as well using signals.
All those animations we looked at so far use signals under the hood.
It's a way to tell a node that something will change over time.
The exposition of an element is a signal just like its opacity or scale.
But you can also add your own signals to custom nodes.
Let's take this emoji as an example.
We can make a new custom node by extending the motion canvas node.
Now that we have our own node, let's add a new signal called silliness and make the length of the tongue depend on the silliness signal.
After adding it to the scene, we can animate the silliness like any other regular signal.
When we want to use signals in the scene directly instead of inside of a custom node, we can do so by using the create signal function.
It will create a new signal object that, for example, stores the radius of a circle.
We can now use this signal and calculate the area of the circle based on that.
This is really helpful when you, for example, want to show the area of the circle on the scene, like it is the case here.
Changing the signal of the radius now will update the area as well.
When writing such animations, you can use wait for to make the scene idle for a bit between the animations themselves.
But synchronizing audio and video just by using animation durations and wait for would be tedious.
So that's why MotionCanvas has a special feature for synchronizing audio with video.
Arguably the most unique MotionCanvas feature is time events.
Instead of using wait for with a fixed value in seconds, you can also use wait until to specify a custom event.
This event then appears in your MotionCanvas editor automatically and can be moved around directly in the editor interface.
This should make synchronizing audio and video a lot easier.
But the reality is, as of recording this voiceover, I have no idea if it actually works well.
So let's ask my future self who is editing this video right now how it is going.
Thank you future self for those amazing insights.
Now that you know how to work with MotionCanvas, what was the process like creating this video?
First of all, a big shout out to Artificial, the creator of MotionCanvas, who did not only do a great job making this library itself, but also documenting it.
The documentation has a lot of examples and is easy to follow, making it a perfect starting point for anyone interested in working with MotionCanvas.
When I started out, I was a little worried about the performance aspect, especially for bigger projects, as motion canvas is just using an HTML canvas and therefore web technology.
But for my use case, it genuinely worked out pretty well.
Scrubbing through the timeline is pretty smooth for the most part.
And overall, it was a much more responsive experience than working with Premiere Pro and After Effects.
So that's a clear win for web technologies yet again.
Another advantage over my previous workflow is that I can actually work on just one screen.
With Premiere Pro and After Effects, I pretty much always had Premiere Pro on one screen and After Effects on the other one.
But with Motion Canvas, a lot of the time I just ended up opening a preview browser inside of Cursor to show the editor, which worked surprisingly well on such a small preview window.
Because of the way motion canvas handles synchronization between audio and video, it also allows me to have a completely different workflow.

Usually I have to record the voiceover before I start editing the video, but with motion canvas, I can just start programming my animations and adopt them as I go along and do the voiceover at the end, which is a real time saver because more often than not, I ended up recording more than one voiceover just because I realized I wanted to change something during the editing process.
But it's not all sunshine and rainbows.
Certain things take a lot more time than just doing them in traditional editing software.
Manually positioning objects or zoom animations can be a real pain as you need to change the value over and over again until you get it to the right position.
The editor interface does not have any drag or drop functionality to modify the position of an element, which makes sense as everything is defined in code, but it can still be very tedious.

While the community is obviously not as big as the one of Premiere Pro or After Effects, you can find components and common patterns in various GitHub repositories as well as on the Motion Canvas Discord server.
I will also link the source code of this video in the description down below.
And if you want to support my other open source work, check out SolidTime, the open source time tracker for your freelance or agency work at solidtime.io.
So, will I use Motion Canvas for my future videos?
Well, I guess you have to subscribe to find out.
Also, if you enjoyed this video, consider leaving a like as it really helps me out.
See you in the next video.
